Slide 1 — Omniverse & Isaac Sim
“For this simulation framework selection, we evaluated several options including Gazebo and Isaac Sim, and ultimately selected NVIDIA’s ecosystem for this project. Let me explain why.
Omniverse is built on USD — Universal Scene Description — which is actually the same format used by Pixar for 3D pipelines, and NVIDIA adopted it as the standard for simulation. The reason this matters for us is that CAD files from SolidWorks can be converted directly to USD format, which means we don’t lose geometric fidelity going from the engineering model to the simulation environment.
Isaac Sim sits on top of Omniverse and is specifically designed for robotics. What makes it particularly relevant for this project is three things: first, it has PhysX integration — NVIDIA’s physics engine — which gives us realistic rigid body dynamics, joint simulation, and contact forces. Second, it supports ROS 2 natively, which is the framework we’d eventually use for the control system. And third, it allows full Python scripting, which means we can programmatically control every aspect of the simulation — from loading assets to driving joints to reading sensor data ”

Slide 2 — Specs
“Let’s talk about hardware because this has been one of our main challenges. Isaac Sim is a GPU-heavy application — it needs the GPU not just for rendering but for physics computation.
Looking at the requirements table, the minimum GPU spec is an RTX 4080 with 16GB VRAM. Our current machine has an RTX A2000 with 8GB VRAM. To put that in perspective — the A2000 is a professional workstation GPU designed for CAD and visualization work, not for real-time physics simulation. It predates the RTX 40 series by several generations. So we’re below the minimum in GPU compute and VRAM capacity.
What this means in practice is that when we load the full borescope assembly plus run real-time physics simulation simultaneously, we start hitting memory limits. This causes slowdowns, occasional crashes during scene loading.
On the RAM side we’re at exactly 32GB which is the minimum — not ideal but workable. Storage is actually fine, we have a 1TB NVMe which meets the ideal spec. CPU is a 12th gen i7 with 16 cores which also meets ideal. So really the bottleneck is specifically GPU and VRAM”

