Slide 5 — Cable simulation video
“This video demonstrates our physics-based cable simulation.
The core problem was this: A cable is not exactly recognized on iIsaac sim so we needed to build it procedurally. 
Our approach is a classic rope simulation technique used in robotics and game physics — we model the cable as a chain of rigid cylindrical segments connected by joints. Each segment is a small cylinder with real physical properties: mass, collision geometry, and damping. The segments are connected by joints that constrain how much they can rotate relative to each other, which gives the cable its stiffness and flexible characteristics.
Specifically we used 40 segments — each 5mm long and 6mm in diameter. Along the main body of the cable we use Fixed Joints with high friction, which gives us a semi-rigid cable that bends under gravity but doesn’t collapse. At the tip we use Spherical Joints with a defined cone angle, which allows the tip to articulate in multiple directions — approximating a 4-DOF motion.
One thing  that I want to mention is that the cable origin is fully dynamic — we compute the world transform of the insertion tube connector at runtime using the USD API, so the cable automatically positions and orients itself correctly regardless of where the borescope assembly is placed or rotated in the scene.”

Slide 6 — Cable + tip movement video
“This second video adds the tip articulation movement that i metioned visually —  here we can see the tip motion going up, down, left, right. 
Technically, the way this works is through Isaac Sim’s physics update loop. Were we inject a velocity command into the last rigid body segment of the cable — the tip. The tip responds to this velocity, and because the rest of the cable segments are connected by joints with physics, they follow naturally — the whole cable deforms in response to the tip movement, which is the behavior you want for a cable simulation.
Right now this is open-loop — the tip follows a predefined movement's . The next step is to replace this with closed-loop position control, where we give the tip a target position and the controller figures out what velocity commands to send.”

Slide 7 — Challenges
“I want to be transparent about the challenges we’re facing because they’re relevant.
The hardware constraint is the most immediate one. The 8GB VRAM limitation means that running the full assembly with real-time physics is close to the memory limit. In practice this means we have to be careful about how many physics objects we have active simultaneously, and we’ve had some instability when loading particularly heavy scenes. For the current cable simulation this is manageable, but as we increase complexity — adding more joints, adding sensor simulation, adding a turbine environment — this will become a harder constraint.
The second challenge is the Omniverse firewall restriction. Right now we’re running Isaac Sim in completely standalone local mode, which means we can’t access Nucleus server, can’t stream assets from Omniverse, and can’t use the cloud-based features. A Fireflow ticket has been submitted and is pending resolution with IT. Once that’s resolved it will significantly improve our workflow — particularly for asset management and for eventually connecting to ROS 2 topics.”

Slide 8 — Next Steps
“Looking ahead, there qre three concrete next steps.
First, refine the cable and tip simulation. The current model is a good first approximation but there are known limitations — the joint model doesn’t perfectly capture the cable-driven kinematics of the real ACB, and the physics parameters need more tuning against real data. 
Second, begin implementing controlled tip articulation. Right now the tip moves on a predefined velocity pattern. What we need is to replace that with a proper joint drive system using position targets — you tell the tip ‘go to 30 degrees up’ and it goes there. This is the foundation for the control simulation. Once we have that, we can start connecting it to a control algorithm and eventually to ROS 2 topics.
Third, explore adding an inspection environment. This means importing an environment into Isaac Sim and positioning the borescope at a realistic entry point. This is important because a lot of the control challenges only become apparent when you’re actually trying to navigate through a constrained geometry — you need walls, blades, and tight clearances to test whether your control system actually works in a realistic scenario.”